sentence: Losses in consumer discretionary and biotech stocks dragged benchmarks lower on Wednesday.
Meanwhile, the continuous rout in global oil prices had a negative impact on energy shares.
Increase in crude, gasoline and distillate stockpiles pulled Brent crude lower.
Wednesday's losses ended a two-day rebound for the Dow and the S&P 500.

For a look at the issues currently facing the markets, make sure to read today's Ahead of Wall Street article

The Dow Jones Industrial Average (DJI) declined 364.81 points or 2.2% to close at 16,151.41.
The Standard & Poor's 500 (S&P 500) dropped 2.5% to close at 1,890.28.
The tech-laden Nasdaq Composite Index closed at 4,526.06, decreasing 3.4%.
The fear-gauge CBOE Volatility Index (VIX) surged 12.2% to settle at 25.22.
A total of around 9.9 billion shares were traded on Wednesday, higher than the last 20-session average of 7.5 billion.
Decliners significantly outpaced advancing stocks on the NYSE.
For 87% stocks that declined, 11% advanced.
The Dow ended the day lower, perilously close to its correction territory which is a drop of 10% or more from its 52-week high.
The S&P 500 and the Nasdaq are already in correction territory.
Meanwhile, both the Dow and the S&P 500 closed at their lowest levels since Sep 29, 2015.
Consumers stocks including retailers, media service firms, durable goods, textile and apparel companies all bore the brunt of the selling pressure on Wednesday.
The Consumer Discretionary Select Sector SPDR (XLY) slumped 3.4%, its worst one-day percentage decline since Aug 24.
It also turned out to be one of the worst performers among the S&P 500 sectors.

Key stocks from the sector including Amazon.com, Inc. ( AMZN ), The Walt Disney Company ( DIS ), The Home Depot, Inc. ( HD ), Comcast Corporation ( CMCSA ) and Netflix, Inc. ( NFLX ) decreased 5.8%, 2.9%, 4.8%, 2.4% and 8.6%, respectively.
Biotech stocks also took a drubbing on Wednesday.

Key biotech stocks including Celgene Corporation ( CELG ), Amgen Inc. ( AMGN ), Gilead Sciences Inc. ( GILD ), Regeneron Pharmaceuticals, Inc. ( REGN ) and Biogen Inc. ( BIIB ) decreased 5.8%, 3.5%, 4.7%, 3.2% and 4.1%, respectively.
The iShares Nasdaq Biotechnology Index (IBB) plunged 5.4%, while the broader Health Care Select Sector SPDR (XLV) declined almost 3%.
Rise in crude stockpiles along with jump in gasoline and distillate supplies had a negative impact on Brent Crude.
The U.S. Energy Information Administration reported that crude inventories increased by 200,000 barrels for the week ending Jan 8.
Additionally, gasoline supplies increased by 8.4 million barrels and distillate stockpiles rose 6.1 million barrels last week.
The Brent Crude declined 1.8% to close at $30.31.
However, U.S. crude managed to eke out gains for the first time in the last eight trading sessions.
The WTI Crude advanced 0.1% to settle at $30.48.
Decline in oil prices adversely affected energy shares.
The Energy Select Sector SPDR (XLE) declined 2.4%.

Key stocks from the energy sectors including Chevron Corporation ( CVX ), Occidental Petroleum Corporation ( OXY ), ConocoPhillips ( COP ), Schlumberger Limited ( SLB ) and Tesoro Corporation ( TSO ) decreased 1%, 0.9%, 3.1%, 1.2% and 12.2%, respectively.
Overall, Wednesday's losses were broad based with all 12 sectors of the S&P 500 ending in the red.
In economic news, the Fed's Beige Book painted a mixed picture of the U.S. economy.
While manufacturing, agricultural and energy sectors are struggling, consumer and housing sectors remains in solid footing.
The Fed's Beige Book showed that 9 out of 12 districts registered modest growth.
The beige book covered economic activity from late November through Jan 4.
